  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Another
  author: Jeong Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: |-
    To gaze upon him is to see a mountain rising majestic and firm,
    A clear pool where waters settle and rest.
    To draw near him is to feel warmth like jade's gentle luster,
    The tender embrace of spring's benevolent sun.

    Who could capture his likeness?
    Such radiant brilliance in form!
    His service to the founding was towering,
    His station supreme among all ministers.

    In serving his lord, his integrity held fast—
    Unwavering through fortune and peril alike.
    In loving his people, the heart of nurture bloomed—
    His care overflowed in all his governance.
    Evil he shunned as one abhors disease,
    Goodness he pursued as the hungry crave sustenance.
    In his own conduct, he stood steadfast in rightness,
    So that none dared deceive him.

    My praise speaks no flattery—
    It is but the voice of all people made manifest.
  footnotes:
    - This work celebrates a virtuous statesman, likely written as a commemorative tribute. The title 'Another' (又) suggests this may be a secondary or supplementary composition on the same subject.
